he representation theory of the locally compact group GLn(K). This book constructs a candidate for such a local Langlands correspondence on the vanishing cycles attached to the bad reduction over the integer ring of K of a certain family of Shimura varieties. And it proves that this is roughly compatible with the global Galois correspondence realized on the cohomology of the same Shimura varieties. The local Langlands conjecture is obtained as a corollary. Certain techniques developed in this book should extend to more general Shimura varieties, providing new instances of the local Langlands conjecture. Moreover, the geometry of the special fibers is strictly analogous to that of Shimura curves and can be expected to have applications to a variety of questions in number theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aMATHEMATICSvGeometryvGeneral. 0aMATHEMATICSvNumber Theory. 0aShimura varieties. 7aMATHEMATICS / Number Theory.2bisacsh  aAbelian variety.  aAbsolute value.  aAlgebraic group.  aAlgebraically closed field.  aArtinian.  aAutomorphic form.  aBase change.  aBijection.  aCanonical map.  aCodimension.  aCoefficient.  aCohomology.  aCompactification (mathematics).  aConjecture.  aCorollary.  aDimension (vector space).  aDimension.  aDirect limit.  aDivision algebra.  aEigenvalues and eigenvectors.  aElliptic curve.  aEmbedding.  aEquivalence class.  aEquivalence of categories.  aExistence theorem.  aField of fractions.  aFinite field.  aFunction field.  aFunctor.  aGalois cohomology.  aGalois group.  aGeneric point.  aGeometry.  aHasse invariant.  aInfinitesimal character.  aInteger.  aInverse system.  aIsomorphism class.  aLie algebra.  aLocal class field theory.  aMaximal torus.  aModular curve.  aModuli space.  aMonic poly